<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-pop-parameters-and-srs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Population Parameters and Sample Statistics</title>
    <p>
        In statistical inference, the concepts of a <em>population</em> and a <em>sample</em> are often described using probability distributions. 
        Rather than thinking of a population simply as a collection of individuals or observations, 
        statisticians represent it by a probability distribution that describes how the values of a variable are expected to occur. 
        This mathematical representation provides the foundation for statistical inference.
    </p>
    <p>
        As an example, consider IQ scores. IQ tests are designed so that scores follow approximately a normal distribution with a mean of 100 and a 
        standard deviation of 15, as illustrated in <xref ref="fig-IQdista"/>. 
        These values describe the entire population and are known as <em>population parameters</em>. 
        The population mean is denoted by <m>\mu</m>, while the population standard deviation is denoted by <m>\sigma</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-IQdista">
        <caption>
            The population distribution of IQ scores, modelled as a normal distribution with mean 100 and standard deviation 15.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/IQdista.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
        Suppose we randomly select 100 individuals from this population and record their IQ scores. The resulting observations form a <em>sample</em>. 
        From this sample, we can calculate quantities such as the sample mean and the sample standard deviation. 
        These are called <em>sample statistics</em> because they are computed from the observed data.
    </p>
    <p>
        Sample statistics are usually close to, but not exactly the same as, the corresponding population parameters. 
        This difference occurs because every random sample is slightly different. Consequently, 
        different samples drawn from the same population generally produce different sample statistics.
    </p>
    <p>
        The distinction between population parameters and sample statistics is fundamental to statistical inference. 
        Population parameters are usually unknown and are the quantities we wish to learn about, while sample statistics provide the information used to estimate them. 
        In the following sections, we introduce methods for obtaining point estimates and confidence intervals, 
        which allow us to estimate population parameters and quantify the uncertainty associated with those estimates.
    </p>
</subsection>